    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-01-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="166"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d166">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.512362 Shipping/8</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Houghton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-22">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 22, 1924</hi>
                        </date>.<lb/>[Received February 12.]</dateline>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 526</seg>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my telegram No. 21 of January 21st
                        last,<note n="84" xml:id="d166fn84">Not printed.</note> with regard to
                    exemption from taxation of individual Americans engaged in shipping, who are
                    non-resident in Germany, and of American shipping companies, I have the honor to
                    transmit herewith a copy and translation of the note from the German Foreign
                    Office, to which my telegram referred.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">A. B. Houghton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
                <frus:attachment>
                    <opener>
                        <seg rendition="#center">[Enclosure—Translation<note n="85"
                                xml:id="d166fn85">File translation revised.</note>]</seg>
                    </opener>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">German Foreign Office</gloss> to
                            the <gloss type="to">American Embassy</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <p rend="flushleft">
                        <hi rend="superscript">No.V Steu 30</hi>/B 2556</p>
                    <p rend="center">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Note Verbale</hi>
                    </p>
                    <p>The Foreign Office has the honor to inform the Embassy of the United States
                        of America, in reply to the latter’s <hi rend="italic">note verbale</hi> of
                            <pb facs="0273" n="191" xml:id="pg_191"/> October 27, 1923 (No.
                            543),<note n="86" xml:id="d166fn86">Not found in Department
                            files.</note> and supplementing its own <hi rend="italic">note
                            verbale</hi> of September 5, 1923 (V Steu 1496),<note n="87"
                            xml:id="d166fn87">See telegram No. 137, Sept. 7, 1923, 9 a.m., from the
                            Ambassador in Germany, <ref target="#pg_188">p. 188</ref>.</note> that,
                        by an ordinance dated January 5, 1924,<note n="88" xml:id="d166fn88">
                            <hi rend="italic">Post</hi>, <ref target="#pg_194">p. 194</ref>.</note>
                        the Federal Minister of Finance has instructed the competent financial
                        authorities that incomes derived from the operation of ships by citizens of
                        the United States of America (individual persons) who have no residence in
                        Germany are likewise to be exempted from the income tax, under the condition
                        of reciprocity and the reservation of repeal at any time, as has already
                        been ordered by a proclamation of August 10, 1923,<note n="89"
                            xml:id="d166fn89">
                            <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_189">p. 189</ref>.</note>
                        relating to American commercial companies as affected by the corporation
                        tax.</p>
                    <p>Furthermore, according to the investigations undertaken by the German
                        Government, citizens of the United States who have no residence in Germany,
                        as well as American shipping companies which receive their incomes from the
                        operation of ships, have not been subjected in Germany to either the income
                        or corporation tax since January 1, 1921.</p>
                    <p>The Foreign Office would be grateful for a statement as to whether now the
                        Government of the United States of America will grant to German shipping
                        companies and individual persons engaged in shipping the same exemption from
                        taxation of incomes derived from the operation of ships, and particularly so
                        with retroactive effect from January 1, 1921.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <dateline rendition="#left">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                            </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-01-19">
                                <hi rend="italic">January 19, 1924</hi>
                            </date>.</dateline>
                    </closer>
                </frus:attachment>
